    "[Item 1 — ~10 sec] ",
    "\"Hi, we're [team name], and our members are [names].\"\n",
    "\n",
    "[Item 2 — ~25 sec] ",
    "\"We're using the CMIP6 dataset — a massive collection of climate model outputs hosted on Google Cloud. Specifically, we're pulling monthly surface air temperature data from NCAR's CESM2 model, which runs from 1850 to 2014. The dataset includes global gridded temperature readings, regional breakdowns, and the area weights needed to compute meaningful global averages.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "[Item 3 — ~55 sec] ",
    "\"To explore the data, we built six graphs. First, a line chart of global mean temperature anomaly over time — this immediately shows the accelerating warming trend. Second, a regional map of the West Coast in August 2014, revealing how heat is distributed spatially. Third, a time series of August temperatures in San Diego specifically, showing local warming over 160 years. Fourth, a bar chart counting extreme heat months per decade in San Diego — the frequency is clearly rising. Fifth, a heatmap of temperature anomaly by latitude and year, which shows polar amplification — the Arctic warming much faster than the tropics. And sixth, a scatterplot of atmospheric CO₂ against global temperature change, which shows a near-linear relationship between the two.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "[Item 4 — ~20 sec] ",
    "\"These graphs led us to one central question: How has the relationship between greenhouse gas concentration and regional temperature extremes evolved over the historical record, and which latitudes are most vulnerable? That's the question our final visualization aims to answer.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "[Item 5 — ~10 sec] ",
    "\"As for our final dynamic graph, we currently have [describe progress].\"\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  }
